# API & Server Action Patterns — pixelAI

## API route structure

All API routes use the Next.js App Router convention — export named `GET`/`POST` handlers, not default exports.

```ts
// ✅ app/api/example/route.ts
export async function GET(req: Request) { ... }
export async function POST(req: Request) { ... }

// ❌
export default function handler(req, res) { ... }
```

## Authentication in API routes

Always verify the session at the top of every protected route. Use `currentUser()` and `currentRole()` from `@/lib/auth.ts`.

```ts
// ✅
import { currentUser, currentRole } from "@/lib/auth";

export async function GET() {
  const user = await currentUser();
  if (!user) return new Response(null, { status: 401 });
  // ...
}
```

Reference: `app/api/data/route.ts` (session check), `app/api/admin/route.ts` (role check).

## Admin routes

Admin-only endpoints must check `role === "ADMIN"` via `currentRole()`:

```ts
// ✅ — follows app/api/admin/route.ts pattern
const role = await currentRole();
if (role !== "ADMIN") return new Response(null, { status: 403 });
```

## Stripe webhook — never skip signature verification

The webhook at `app/api/webhooks/stripe/route.ts` must always verify the Stripe signature. This is a security-critical check.

```ts
// ✅ required pattern
const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(body, sig, process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET!);
```

Never bypass or comment out this check.

## Server Actions

Server Actions live in `lib/actions/`. They are `async` functions — not API routes. Follow this shape:

```ts
// ✅ pattern from lib/actions/image.actions.ts
export async function addImage({ image, userId, path }: AddImageParams) {
  try {
    const newImage = await db.image.create({ data: { ...image, author: { connect: { id: userId } } } });
    revalidatePath(path);
    return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(newImage));
  } catch (error) {
    handleError(error);
  }
}
```

Rules:
- Always return `{ success: "..." }` or `{ error: "..." }` shapes when communicating outcomes to the UI
- Never throw raw errors to the client — catch and return `{ error: "..." }`
- Call `revalidatePath()` or `revalidateTag()` after mutations to keep the cache fresh

## Input validation

Validate all inputs with a Zod schema from `@/schemas/index.ts` before any DB write.

```ts
// ✅
const validated = LoginSchema.safeParse(values);
if (!validated.success) return { error: "Invalid fields" };
const { email, password } = validated.data;
```

## Database access

Only use `db` from `@/lib/db.ts`. Never instantiate `PrismaClient` directly.

```ts
import { db } from "@/lib/db";
const image = await db.image.findUnique({ where: { id } });
```

## Credits deduction

Never write to `User.creditBalance` directly. Always use `updateCredits()` from `@/data/user.ts`:

```ts
// ✅
import { updateCredits } from "@/data/user";
await updateCredits(userId, creditFee); // creditFee = -1
```

## Error handling

```ts
// ✅
} catch (error) {
  handleError(error);
  return { error: "Something went wrong" };
}
```

Never use empty `catch` blocks. Never re-throw `error` directly from a Server Action.
